---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleQuiz from "../../../components/module/ModuleQuiz.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "65-security";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="65 · Security for GenAI">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Every module so far has assumed the documents in your index are trustworthy and the model's output is safe to
        show a user. Security is where both assumptions get tested — because a working RAG pipeline is, by default,
        wide open to both.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <h2>Direct and indirect prompt injection</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Direct injection</strong> is a user typing "ignore your instructions and..." into the chat box — annoying,
      but scoped to that one user's own session. <strong>Indirect injection</strong> is worse: a malicious instruction
      hidden inside a document that later gets ingested (back in Module 10) and retrieved (Module 35). Because the
      model can't distinguish "trusted system instructions" from "text that happened to come back from retrieval," one
      poisoned document in the index attacks every future query that retrieves it — not just its author's own
      questions.
    </p>

    <h2>Data exfiltration via retrieval</h2>
    <p>
      Retrieval finds the most semantically similar chunk, full stop — it has no concept of "whose document this is"
      unless you tell it. If the index mixes multiple tenants or users without a document-level ACL filter applied at
      query time, one tenant's question can surface another tenant's private chunks. This isn't a hypothetical: it's
      the direct consequence of skipping the access-control step that Module 20's embeddings work doesn't force you to
      think about.
    </p>

    <h2>Jailbreaks vs. injection</h2>
    <p>
      It's worth keeping these distinct. A <strong>jailbreak</strong> targets the model's own safety training,
      usually through the user's own prompt, to get it to say something it normally wouldn't. <strong>Injection</strong>
      doesn't need to break any safety training at all — it just smuggles instructions in through data the model
      treats as part of its context, exploiting the fact that the model can't tell instructions from content.
    </p>

    <h2>Output handling: treat model output as untrusted</h2>
    <p>
      If your frontend renders the model's answer as HTML without sanitizing it, and an attacker manages (via
      injection) to get the model to emit a <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag, you have an XSS vulnerability that
      originates from your own LLM. The fix is the same one web security has always taught: never trust input you
      didn't fully control the generation of, and model output — shaped by retrieved documents you don't fully
      control — qualifies. The <strong>OWASP LLM Top 10</strong> catalogs this and the injection/exfiltration risks
      above under a shared vocabulary worth knowing before you ship a RAG app to real users.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Assuming injection requires a malicious user — a single poisoned document ingested from an untrusted source can attack every future query.</li>
      <li>Skipping document-level access-control filters on retrieval because "we'll add multi-tenancy later" — by then the index already mixes everyone's data.</li>
      <li>Rendering LLM output directly as HTML without sanitization, treating it as if it came from your own trusted code.</li>
      <li>Conflating jailbreak defenses with injection defenses — a model resistant to jailbreaks can still be hijacked by injected content in retrieved context.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleQuiz moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
